const COURSE_DATA = {"zh":{"01-intro":"# 01. 课程导读 — 用 AI 重画创业地图\n\n2026 年 5 月，Anthropic 发布了《The Founder's Playbook: Building an AI-Native Startup》（《创始人手册：打造 AI 原生创业公司》）。这是一本写给\"在 AI 时代从零做产品\"的创始人的实战手册，把创业的四个经典阶段——构想（Idea）、最小可行产品（MVP）、发布（Launch）、规模化（Scale）——按 2026 年的现实重新画了一遍。\n\n本课程把这本手册的核心方法整理成 6 个模块，供中文读者快速对照原文使用。**所有原始内容版权归 Anthropic 所有**，本课程仅作为学习导航与中文注解。\n\n## 为什么需要一本\"新\"创业手册\n\n过去十年的创业方法论（精益创业、Y Combinator 那一套）默认的前提是：\n- 工程师稀缺 → MVP 要小、要省人\n- 客户访谈要靠双脚 → 销售周期长\n- 产品迭代要靠工程团队 → 招人是瓶颈\n\n到了 2026 年，AI 把这三个前提全都打破了：\n\n| 旧默认 | AI 原生时代 |\n|--------|------------|\n| 工程师稀缺，MVP 要\"最小\" | 工程产能近乎免费，MVP 要\"最值得\" |\n| 客户访谈靠双脚 | 客户研究可以并行批量做 |\n| 招人是瓶颈 | 招人变成\"agent 招架\"问题 |\n| 营收先于规模 | **营收依然先于规模**（这条没变） |\n\n最后一条没变，但因为前三条变了，**到达营收的路径完全不同了**。这就是手册要解决的问题。\n\n## 四阶段地图\n\n| 阶段 | 核心问题 | 退出标准 |\n|------|---------|----------|\n| **Idea**（构想） | 我要解决的问题真的存在吗？ | 已找到至少 10 个愿意付费的目标客户 |\n| **MVP**（最小可行产品） | 我能不能用最低成本造出\"管用\"的版本？ | 产品能让首批客户完整跑一遍业务流程 |\n| **Launch**（发布） | 这是真 PMF 还是早期幻觉？ | 留存与口碑数据稳定 4 周以上 |\n| **Scale**（规模化） | 从单兵作战切到团队/agentic 运营 | 关键流程可在创始人不在场时跑通 |\n\n每个阶段，手册都给出：\n- **Goals**（目标）\n- **Exit criteria**（退出标准）\n- **Common failure modes**（常见失败模式）\n- **AI-powered exercises**（AI 驱动的练习）\n\n后续 4 个模块（02–05）逐一展开。\n\n## 工具矩阵：Chat / Cowork / Code\n\nAnthropic 在手册中提供了一张\"什么阶段用什么工具\"的矩阵。简化版如下：\n\n| 阶段 | 主力工具 | 用法举例 |\n|------|---------|----------|\n| Idea | **Chat**（Claude.ai 对话） | 跑客户访谈脚本、画竞品地图、写问题假设 |\n| MVP | **Claude Code** | 直接生成 MVP 代码、修 bug、写测试 |\n| Launch | **Cowork** + Code | 跑营销流、内容生成、客户反馈分类 |\n| Scale | **Cowork** 多 agent | 把\"创始人注意力\"换成 agentic workflow |\n\n> Coffee CLI 用户提示：上表里的 **Claude Code** 是命令行工具——在 Coffee CLI 桌面应用里新开一个 Claude Code 标签页就能运行。**Cowork** 和 **Chat** 是网页应用，在 [claude.ai](https://claude.ai) 中使用。\n\n## 如何使用本课程\n\n1. **第一遍快速过**：把 02–05 四个模块的标题和退出标准看一遍，建立阶段感\n2. **对照原文**：访问下方\"原文与资源\"链接下载 Anthropic 官方 PDF\n3. **回到自己的项目**：对每个阶段的\"失败模式\"自检，看自己当前卡在哪里\n4. **6 模块案例**：读完后看 06，6 家创业公司的实战故事\n\n## 原文与资源\n\n- **官方介绍页**：https://claude.com/blog/the-founders-playbook\n- **官方 PDF 下载**：[The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3.pdf](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n- **社区中文翻译**：[yangliu2060/founders-playbook-zh](https://github.com/yangliu2060/founders-playbook-zh)（含中文信息图表）\n- **双语对照版**：[glassesmonkey/founders-playbook-claude-zh](https://github.com/glassesmonkey/founders-playbook-claude-zh)（仿沉浸式翻译排版）\n- **繁體中文版**：[naer-tw/founders-playbook-tw](https://github.com/naer-tw/founders-playbook-tw)\n","02-idea":"# 02. Idea 阶段 — 验证问题假设\n\n> **退出标准**：你能列出至少 10 个清楚说出\"愿意为此付费\"的具体客户，并且他们的问题描述高度一致。\n\n构想阶段最容易死的方式不是\"想不到点子\"，而是**爱上一个没人要的点子**。AI 把这个阶段的工作量降了一个数量级——你不再需要找投资人聊三个月，不再需要花两周做调研报告。但 AI 不会替你判断\"这个问题值不值得做\"，它只会让你跑得更快。跑错方向的话，跑得更快意味着死得更快。\n\n## 阶段目标\n\n1. **找到一个真问题**：不是\"我觉得有人会需要\"，而是\"我已经在 N 个独立场景看到了同一个痛点\"\n2. **画出竞品地图**：现有的解法是什么？为什么它们不够好？AI 是不是改变了\"够好\"的定义？\n3. **找到第一批愿意付费的客户画像**：不是\"所有 SaaS 用户\"，而是\"做 X 行业的 Y 角色，每周被 Z 问题困扰\"\n\n## AI 驱动的三个练习\n\n### 练习 1：问题假设画布\n\n让 Claude 帮你写一份**问题假设清单**，每条 1 句话，结构是：\n\n> \"**[谁]** 在做 **[什么场景]** 时，遇到 **[什么痛点]**，目前用 **[什么变通方案]** 应对，这个变通方案的代价是 **[多少时间/钱]**。\"\n\n强迫自己写满 20 条。前 5 条都是脑海里的，第 6 条之后才开始挑战自己的认知。\n\n### 练习 2：批量客户访谈脚本\n\n传统访谈：1 周约 3 个人，问 5 个问题，记录手写。  \nAI 时代：让 Claude 同时帮你生成 20 个行业 × 3 个角色 × 5 个问题的访谈脚本，你只需要选 5 个最相关的去执行。\n\n**注意**：AI 生成的访谈脚本是\"起点\"，不是\"终点\"。真正的洞察来自 follow-up question——而 follow-up question 必须人去问。\n\n### 练习 3：竞品对手地图\n\n用 Claude 跑一遍：\n1. 列出当前市场上解决这个问题的所有产品（直接对手 + 间接对手 + DIY 方案）\n2. 对每个对手，列出\"它的核心承诺 / 它的售价 / 它的最大短板\"\n3. 标记出\"AI 之前不可能做、AI 之后才可能\"的空白区\n\n那个空白区，就是你的机会。\n\n## 常见失败模式\n\n| 失败模式 | 原因 | 怎么破 |\n|---------|------|--------|\n| **只跟\"愿意聊\"的人聊** | Survivor bias 极强 | 强制每周聊 2 个\"明显不会买\"的人 |\n| **把\"觉得好用\"当成\"愿意付费\"** | 这是两件事 | 直接问\"如果它一年 ¥1200 你会买吗\" |\n| **过早爱上技术方案** | 工程师创业的通病 | 前 30 天禁止打开 IDE |\n| **把竞品地图做成 SWOT** | SWOT 不能指导决策 | 改成\"空白区 + 价格段\"二维图 |\n| **以为 AI 能替你判断方向** | AI 没有 taste | AI 负责生成，你负责筛选 |\n\n## 退出 Idea 阶段的检查清单\n\n进入下一阶段（MVP）之前，确保你能回答：\n\n- [ ] 我能在 30 秒内说清楚我要解决谁的什么问题\n- [ ] 我有至少 10 个具名的目标客户（不是\"所有 SaaS 公司\"）\n- [ ] 我知道他们现在用什么方案应对，以及那个方案的代价\n- [ ] 我能说出\"AI 之前不可能，AI 之后才可能\"的那个差异点\n- [ ] 至少 3 个客户口头承诺\"如果你做出来，我会试用 / 付费\"\n\n如果有任何一项是\"差不多\"或\"应该\"，**不要进入 MVP 阶段**。回去多聊 10 个人。\n\n## 原文与资源\n\n- 本模块基于 Anthropic《The Founder's Playbook》Idea 章节整理\n- 原版 PDF：[官方下载链接](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n","03-mvp":"# 03. MVP 阶段 — 造出\"刚刚好\"的产品\n\n> **退出标准**：首批客户可以用你的产品完整跑一遍业务流程，不需要你在旁边\"手动救场\"。\n\nMVP 阶段最大的变化：**写代码不再是瓶颈**。一个创始人配上 Claude Code，一周内可以做出过去三人小队三个月才能做出的功能集。但产能爆炸带来一个新陷阱——**架构和安全债比代码量增长得更快**。\n\n## 阶段目标\n\n1. **造出\"端到端\"可用的版本**，而不是漂亮的局部 demo\n2. **架构选型要为\"3 个月后还要改\"留余地**，不是\"先跑通再说\"\n3. **从第一天就把安全做对**，因为 AI 生成的代码默认不安全\n4. **建立可衡量的客户反馈通路**，准备进入 Launch 阶段\n\n## 架构与范围\n\n### 三条范围红线\n\nAI 代码生成快不代表你应该全做。MVP 阶段死守以下三条：\n\n1. **不做付费/支付**：先用 Stripe Payment Link 或人工开发票，省 1 个月工程量\n2. **不做后台管理界面**：用 Retool / Airtable + 数据库直连，省 2 周\n3. **不做用户角色权限系统**：所有人都是 admin，等 Launch 后再加\n\n> 这三条加起来能省你 2 个月。把这 2 个月用在客户访谈和迭代上。\n\n### 架构选型的\"3 个月规则\"\n\n问每一个技术决策：\n\n> \"3 个月后我要改这个，代价是多少？\"\n\n- 数据库选 Postgres，不是 NoSQL：3 个月后想加复杂查询，Postgres 不会卡你\n- 后端用单体，不是微服务：3 个月后想拆服务，单体很容易拆；反过来很难合\n- 前端用一个框架，不要混：3 个月后招人，一个框架的人好招\n\n**AI 不会替你做这些选型**，因为它不知道你 3 个月后想干嘛。这是创始人的活。\n\n## 安全实践\n\nAI 生成的代码默认有以下问题：\n\n| 问题 | 表现 | 怎么修 |\n|------|------|--------|\n| **SQL 注入** | 字符串拼接 SQL | 强制用参数化查询 / ORM |\n| **硬编码密钥** | API key 写在代码里 | `.env` + 检查 .gitignore |\n| **任意文件读** | path traversal | 白名单 + path.resolve 校验 |\n| **CORS 配错** | `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` | 显式列域名 |\n| **没有 rate limit** | 一个用户能把服务跑挂 | 用 Cloudflare / 框架中间件 |\n\n**在 MVP 阶段就装这些 guardrail**，比上线后修便宜 10 倍。\n\n## 防止技术债爆炸\n\n### 给 Claude Code 立规矩\n\n在项目根目录建 `CLAUDE.md`（或对应 `AGENTS.md`），明确写：\n\n```\n- 所有数据库查询用 prepared statement\n- 不允许在代码里写硬编码 secret\n- 新功能必须有至少 1 个集成测试\n- 修改超过 50 行的 PR 必须先写一段设计说明\n```\n\n这是给 AI 看的\"项目宪法\"。Claude Code、Cursor、Aider 都会读它。\n\n### 每周一次\"债务清盘\"\n\n每周固定 2 小时，让 Claude 跑一次：\n\n> \"扫一遍项目，找出：1) 重复了 3 次以上的代码片段；2) 没有测试覆盖的关键路径；3) 不符合 CLAUDE.md 规则的地方。\"\n\n把扫出来的前 3 项当周修掉。剩下的可以等。\n\n## 常见失败模式\n\n| 失败模式 | 原因 | 怎么破 |\n|---------|------|--------|\n| **造成\"演示型 MVP\"** | 只能演示 happy path，真用就崩 | 强制让 3 个客户独立完整跑一遍 |\n| **过早优化性能** | \"10 万用户怎么办\" | 10 万用户是 Scale 阶段的问题 |\n| **AI 写多少接多少** | 不读代码就 commit | 每个 PR 至少看一遍 diff |\n| **每个功能都自己造** | \"不依赖第三方\" | MVP 阶段不存在\"过度依赖\"，能买就买 |\n| **没有客户反馈通路** | 上线后才想起来要反馈 | 第一天就建客户群 / 留邮箱按钮 |\n\n## 退出 MVP 阶段的检查清单\n\n- [ ] 首批 3 个客户能不靠你完整跑一遍核心流程\n- [ ] 关键安全检查项都通过（SQL/密钥/CORS/rate limit）\n- [ ] 项目根目录有 `CLAUDE.md` 并被实际遵守\n- [ ] 你能在 1 周内 ship 一个新功能（不会被技术债拖住）\n- [ ] 有渠道能 24 小时内收到客户反馈\n\n如果\"首批客户独立跑通\"这条没达成，**不要进入 Launch**。继续打磨。\n\n## 原文与资源\n\n- 本模块基于 Anthropic《The Founder's Playbook》MVP 章节整理\n- Coffee CLI 用户：在 Coffee CLI 桌面应用里开 Claude Code 标签页运行，并在项目根目录建 `CLAUDE.md`\n- 原版 PDF：[官方下载链接](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n","04-launch":"# 04. Launch 阶段 — 区分 PMF 与早期幻觉\n\n> **退出标准**：核心指标（留存 / 推荐 / 付费转化）稳定 4 周以上不下滑，并且你能说清楚\"为什么\"。\n\n发布阶段是创业最容易自我欺骗的阶段。Twitter 上的好评、Product Hunt 的当日榜首、媒体的报道——这些都不是 PMF。它们是**烟花**。区分烟花和真火，是 Launch 阶段的核心功夫。\n\n## 阶段目标\n\n1. **找到一个有意义的留存信号**（不是 vanity metrics）\n2. **建立 agentic 营销/运营工作流**，把创始人从重复劳动里拔出来\n3. **判断是真 PMF 还是早期炒作**，决定是 Scale 还是回 MVP\n4. **从\"我推产品\"切到\"产品自己长\"**\n\n## PMF 衡量框架\n\n### 一个核心问题\n\nSean Ellis 的经典问题至今有效：\n\n> \"如果明天这个产品消失了，你会有多失望？\"\n\n四个候选答案：\n\n- 非常失望\n- 有点失望\n- 不会失望\n- 我已经不用了\n\n**40% 以上选\"非常失望\"** = 触摸到 PMF 的边了。低于这个数，回去打磨。\n\n### 三个不会撒谎的指标\n\n烟花指标：DAU、注册数、发推热度  \n**真火指标**：\n\n1. **D7 / D30 留存**：用户 7 天后还在用吗？30 天后呢？\n2. **付费转化率**：免费试用 → 付费的比例，连续 4 周稳定 ≥ 5%\n3. **自然推荐率**：新用户里有多少是\"朋友/同事推荐来的\"\n\n**4 周稳定** 比\"有过一次峰值\"重要 10 倍。\n\n### 不要数 vanity metrics\n\n| 烟花指标 | 真火指标 |\n|---------|---------|\n| Product Hunt 排名 | 上线 30 天后的 DAU |\n| Twitter follower 数 | 邮件订阅 → 注册转化 |\n| 媒体报道数量 | 自然搜索流量增长 |\n| 当日注册量 | D30 留存 |\n\n## Agentic 运营工作流\n\n发布之后，创始人的注意力会被以下事情吃光：\n\n- 回客户邮件 / Discord\n- 写营销内容（推文、博客、case study）\n- 跑数据分析\n- 处理客户反馈分类\n\n**把这些都交给 agent**，留出 80% 的时间做\"只有创始人能做\"的事（产品方向、关键招聘、关键客户）。\n\n### 一个典型的 agentic 营销栈\n\n| 工作 | 工具 | 谁做 |\n|------|------|------|\n| 客户反馈分类 | Claude + Linear/Notion API | Agent 全自动 |\n| 周报数据汇总 | Claude Code + dbt | Agent 全自动，创始人审 |\n| 内容初稿（推文、博客） | Cowork | Agent 写，创始人改 |\n| 客户邮件回复 | Claude.ai 模板 + 人工发 | Agent 起草，创始人按钮发 |\n| 关键客户跟进 | **创始人亲自** | 不要让 agent 碰 |\n\n最后一条划线：**关键客户必须创始人亲自跟**。这是 agent 不能替代的。\n\n## 常见失败模式\n\n| 失败模式 | 原因 | 怎么破 |\n|---------|------|--------|\n| **把烟花当成真火** | 上线当周数据爆炸，以为成了 | 等满 4 周再判断 |\n| **过早烧钱做付费投放** | \"再加一倍预算流量会更好\" | 先做到自然增长 ≥ 5%/周再投钱 |\n| **创始人继续手动回复一切** | \"客户体验\" | 一天投入 ≤ 2 小时手动，剩下让 agent 干 |\n| **PMF 没到就开始招人** | \"再来 3 个工程师我们就赢了\" | 没 PMF 招人 = 放大错误 |\n| **以为 PMF 是一个点** | \"我们找到 PMF 了\" | PMF 是一段持续状态，会丢，要守 |\n\n## 退出 Launch 阶段的检查清单\n\n- [ ] D30 留存 ≥ 30%（B2B SaaS）或 ≥ 40%（C 端高频）\n- [ ] 付费转化连续 4 周 ≥ 5%\n- [ ] 至少 20% 新用户来自自然推荐\n- [ ] 创始人每天用在重复劳动上的时间 ≤ 2 小时\n- [ ] 你能用一句话说清\"为什么用户留下来\"\n\n如果\"为什么留下来\"答不上，那不是真 PMF，是运气。继续观察。\n\n## 原文与资源\n\n- 本模块基于 Anthropic《The Founder's Playbook》Launch 章节整理\n- Sean Ellis 的 PMF 问卷模板：搜索 \"Sean Ellis PMF Survey\"\n- 原版 PDF：[官方下载链接](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n","05-scale":"# 05. Scale 阶段 — 从单兵到 agentic 团队\n\n> **退出标准**：关键业务流程在创始人不在场时依然能跑通，并且团队（人 + agent）每周都能交付。\n\n规模化阶段不再是\"创始人 + AI\"，而是\"创始人 + 团队 + AI\"。这里出现了 AI 原生公司最反直觉的事实：**招的第一个人不一定是工程师**。因为 AI 已经把工程产能拉满了，瓶颈在别的地方——销售、客户成功、运营。\n\n## 阶段目标\n\n1. **从\"创始人英雄主义\"切到可复制的流程**\n2. **决定哪些事招人做、哪些事招 agent 做**\n3. **建立可持续的财务模型**（不再靠融资续命）\n4. **保住 PMF**，因为规模化最容易把 PMF 搞丢\n\n## 招人 vs 招 agent 决策框架\n\n每个新增工作，先问三个问题：\n\n1. **它是判断密集，还是执行密集？**\n   - 执行密集 → agent\n   - 判断密集 → 人\n2. **它需要客户信任吗？**\n   - 需要 → 人（关键销售、客户成功）\n   - 不需要 → agent\n3. **错了的代价多大？**\n   - 高代价（合同、产品方向） → 人\n   - 低代价（写初稿、整理数据） → agent\n\n### 典型分工\n\n| 工作类型 | 谁做 | 原因 |\n|---------|------|------|\n| 写销售邮件初稿 | Agent | 执行密集，错了改就行 |\n| 谈年合同 | 人（创始人 / 销售头） | 高代价 + 需要信任 |\n| 写技术文档 | Agent + 工程师审 | Agent 出稿，人保证准 |\n| 客户 onboarding | 人（C 端可以 agent） | B2B 需要信任，C 端不需要 |\n| 数据看板 | Agent + 工程师审架构 | 执行密集 |\n| 招聘面试 | 人 | 判断密集 + 客户信任的反向 |\n\n## 财务模型\n\nScale 阶段必须切到\"营收驱动\"，不再靠融资续命：\n\n### 三个数你必须每周看\n\n1. **MRR（月度经常收入）**：增长率，最好月环比 ≥ 15%\n2. **CAC payback 时间**：获客成本多久能回本，应 ≤ 12 个月\n3. **现金跑道**：手上的钱够烧多久，应 ≥ 12 个月\n\n### AI 原生公司的财务优势\n\n| 项 | 传统 SaaS | AI 原生 |\n|----|----------|--------|\n| 工程师人头 | 高 | 低（AI 替代） |\n| 客户成功人头 | 高 | 中（部分 agent 化） |\n| 营销内容产出 | 慢 + 贵 | 快 + 便宜 |\n| 毛利率 | 70-80% | 80-90% |\n\n**毛利率 +10% 是巨大的优势**——意味着同样营收下你能投入更多到产品和销售。\n\n## 保住 PMF\n\nScale 阶段最大的隐性风险：**你以为在 Scale 已有的 PMF，其实在悄悄丢**。\n\n### 三个早期信号\n\n1. **新客户留存下滑**（D30 从 40% 跌到 30%）\n2. **客服 ticket 类型变化**（从 \"怎么用\" 变成 \"为什么这样设计\"）\n3. **创始人不再亲自见客户**（最危险）\n\n### 怎么守\n\n- **创始人每周至少见 5 个客户**，无论公司多大\n- **客户反馈每周一次走读**，agent 分类，创始人亲自看 top 10\n- **不为 Scale 而 Scale**——增长速度低于团队膨胀速度时，立即收缩\n\n## 常见失败模式\n\n| 失败模式 | 原因 | 怎么破 |\n|---------|------|--------|\n| **过早招高级工程师** | \"我们要 scale 工程\" | AI 已经替了 80%，先招销售/CS |\n| **创始人退到二线** | \"我要做战略\" | 还没到时候，继续亲自见客户 |\n| **靠融资续命** | \"再融一轮就好\" | Scale 阶段必须营收驱动 |\n| **复制硅谷打法** | \"OpenAI/Anthropic 那么干\" | 你不是 OpenAI，你是你 |\n| **agent 跑无人区** | 全自动化，没人审 | 关键决策点必须有人 |\n\n## 退出 Scale 阶段（或承认还没到）的检查清单\n\n- [ ] MRR 月环比 ≥ 15%（连续 6 个月）\n- [ ] CAC payback ≤ 12 个月\n- [ ] 现金跑道 ≥ 12 个月\n- [ ] 关键流程文档化，新人 1 周能上手\n- [ ] 创始人每周仍亲自见 ≥ 5 个客户\n- [ ] D30 留存没有下滑\n\n如果有 2 项以上未达标，**回到 Launch 阶段**重新打磨。Scale 是结果不是目标。\n\n## 原文与资源\n\n- 本模块基于 Anthropic《The Founder's Playbook》Scale 章节整理\n- 原版 PDF：[官方下载链接](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n","06-stories":"# 06. 创始人案例 — 六家公司的实战故事\n\nAnthropic 在《The Founder's Playbook》里挑了 6 家正在用 Claude 跑 AI 原生模式的早期公司，作为案例研究。它们覆盖了不同行业（医疗、企业工具、消费应用、agent 基础设施），共同点是：**小团队、AI 重度使用、营收驱动**。\n\n> 以下案例信息均基于 Anthropic 官方手册公开内容整理。每家公司的详细故事请以官方原文为准。\n\n## Ambral\n\n**行业**：企业应用 / 自动化  \n**模式**：小团队 + Claude Code 重度使用，把企业流程自动化做到\"按结果收费\"\n\n**关键看点**：\n- 从一开始就用 AI 写代码，工程人头压到最低\n- 销售采用\"先免费跑出 ROI、再签合同\"的模式\n- 客户成功大量 agent 化\n\n## Anything\n\n**行业**：消费应用 / 创意工具  \n**模式**：把 AI 能力包装成\"普通人也能用\"的创作工具\n\n**关键看点**：\n- UX 优先：把 AI 的\"魔法时刻\"做到 10 秒内\n- 增长靠用户自发分享，几乎不投放\n- 创始人继续亲自做产品 + 见用户\n\n## Carta Healthcare\n\n**行业**：医疗 / 临床数据  \n**模式**：用 AI 处理临床试验的非结构化数据\n\n**关键看点**：\n- 强监管行业 + AI = 极高门槛，护城河天然深\n- 销售周期长，但 ACV（年合同价值）极高\n- 工程团队小，但合规和领域专家配比高\n\n## HumanLayer\n\n**行业**：Agent 基础设施  \n**模式**：给 agent 加\"人类审批\"层，让自动化系统在关键决策点等人\n\n**关键看点**：\n- 卖给\"做 agent 的人\"——dev tools 玩家\n- 完美契合 Scale 阶段的\"agent + 人\"分工框架\n- 创始人本身就是 agent 框架的深度用户\n\n## Vulcan Technologies\n\n**行业**：B2B / 工业自动化  \n**模式**：把传统工业软件的\"半手工\"流程用 AI 重做\n\n**关键看点**：\n- 老行业 + AI 是当前最被低估的赛道\n- 客户付费意愿高，但教育周期长\n- 销售必须创始人亲自做（信任问题）\n\n## 第六家公司\n\nAnthropic 原文还提到一家公司，未在本课程整理范围内。请参考[官方手册 PDF](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf) 第三部分获取完整案例。\n\n## 共同模式\n\n把 6 个案例横向对比，能看到几个共同特征：\n\n| 共同点 | 解释 |\n|--------|------|\n| **团队 < 20 人** | AI 让小团队也能做出过去需要 50 人的事 |\n| **创始人 / 工程比 ≥ 1:3** | 不是工程师堆人，是 AI 杠杆 |\n| **客户成功 / 销售比 ≥ 1:1** | 销售依然重要，不是只靠产品自传播 |\n| **毛利率 > 80%** | AI 带来的成本结构优势 |\n| **创始人亲见客户** | 无论团队多大，这条不变 |\n\n## 怎么用这些案例\n\n读案例最容易犯的错：**记住故事忘记原则**。\n\n正确读法：\n1. 先读案例，记住\"它做对了什么\"\n2. 回到 02-05 模块，对应到具体阶段\n3. 问自己：\"我现在的阶段，应该模仿它哪一招？\"\n4. **不要直接复制商业模式**——你不是它\n\n## 原文与资源\n\n- 完整案例细节请查阅 Anthropic 原版 PDF：[官方下载链接](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n- Anthropic 介绍页：https://claude.com/blog/the-founders-playbook\n- 各公司官网请自行搜索\n"},"en":{"01-intro":"# 01. Introduction — Remapping Startup for the AI-Native Era\n\nIn May 2026, Anthropic published *The Founder's Playbook: Building an AI-Native Startup*. It remaps the four classic startup stages — Idea, MVP, Launch, Scale — for the reality of 2026, when one founder + Claude Code can ship what used to take a three-person team three months.\n\nThis course distills the playbook into 6 modules for quick reference. **All original content is © Anthropic.** This course serves as a study companion and Chinese-language gateway.\n\n## Why a New Playbook\n\nThe old startup playbook (Lean Startup, YC) assumed:\n- Engineers are scarce → keep the MVP small\n- Customer discovery requires legwork → long sales cycles\n- Product iteration needs an engineering team → hiring is the bottleneck\n\nIn 2026, AI broke all three assumptions:\n\n| Old default | AI-native era |\n|-------------|---------------|\n| Engineers scarce → \"smallest\" MVP | Engineering nearly free → \"most valuable\" MVP |\n| Customer research is slow | Research can run in parallel batches |\n| Hiring is the bottleneck | Hiring agents is the new bottleneck |\n| Revenue before scale | **Revenue still comes before scale** (unchanged) |\n\nThe last point holds — but because the first three changed, **the path to revenue is completely different**. That's what the playbook addresses.\n\n## The Four-Stage Map\n\n| Stage | Core question | Exit criteria |\n|-------|--------------|---------------|\n| **Idea** | Does the problem really exist? | 10+ specific paying-ready customers |\n| **MVP** | Can I build a working version cheaply? | First customers can complete the core flow |\n| **Launch** | Real PMF or early hype? | Retention/word-of-mouth stable 4+ weeks |\n| **Scale** | Solo to team/agent-driven ops | Key flows run when founder is absent |\n\nEach stage gets **Goals**, **Exit criteria**, **Common failure modes**, and **AI-powered exercises** in modules 02–05.\n\n## Tool Matrix: Chat / Cowork / Code\n\n| Stage | Primary tool | Example |\n|-------|------------|---------|\n| Idea | **Chat** (Claude.ai) | Customer interviews, competitive maps, hypotheses |\n| MVP | **Claude Code** | Generate MVP code, fix bugs, write tests |\n| Launch | **Cowork** + Code | Marketing flows, content, feedback triage |\n| Scale | **Cowork** multi-agent | Replace founder attention with agentic workflow |\n\n> Coffee CLI users: **Claude Code** in the table above is a CLI tool — open it as a new tab in the Coffee CLI desktop app. **Cowork** and **Chat** are web apps, used on [claude.ai](https://claude.ai).\n\n## How to Use This Course\n\n1. **First pass**: skim modules 02–05 to grasp the stage flow\n2. **Reference original**: download the Anthropic PDF below\n3. **Self-audit**: check the failure-mode list for each stage against your project\n4. **Read 06 last**: case studies from 6 real AI-native startups\n\n## Original Sources\n\n- **Official intro**: https://claude.com/blog/the-founders-playbook\n- **Official PDF**: [The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3.pdf](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n- **Community Chinese translation**: [yangliu2060/founders-playbook-zh](https://github.com/yangliu2060/founders-playbook-zh)\n- **Bilingual version**: [glassesmonkey/founders-playbook-claude-zh](https://github.com/glassesmonkey/founders-playbook-claude-zh)\n- **Traditional Chinese**: [naer-tw/founders-playbook-tw](https://github.com/naer-tw/founders-playbook-tw)\n","02-idea":"# 02. Idea Stage — Validate the Problem Hypothesis\n\n> **Exit criteria**: You can name 10+ specific customers who would pay, and their problem descriptions converge.\n\nThe fastest way to die in the Idea stage isn't failing to come up with an idea — it's **falling in love with an idea nobody wants**. AI cuts the workload here by an order of magnitude, but it won't judge \"is this worth doing.\" It just makes you go faster. Faster in the wrong direction means dying faster.\n\n## Stage Goals\n\n1. **Find a real problem** — not \"I think people would want this,\" but \"I've seen the same pain in N independent scenarios\"\n2. **Map the competition** — what exists, why isn't it good enough, did AI redefine \"good enough\"?\n3. **Identify the first paying-ready persona** — not \"all SaaS users,\" but \"X-industry Y-roles bothered weekly by Z\"\n\n## Three AI-Powered Exercises\n\n### Exercise 1: Problem-Hypothesis Canvas\n\nHave Claude help you write 20 one-line problem hypotheses in the structure:\n\n> \"**[Who]** doing **[what task]** hits **[what pain]**, currently workarounds it with **[what kludge]**, paying a cost of **[how much time/money]**.\"\n\nForce yourself to fill all 20. The first 5 are from your head; entries 6+ are where you start challenging assumptions.\n\n### Exercise 2: Batch Interview Scripts\n\nOld way: 3 interviews/week, hand-recorded.\nNew way: have Claude generate 20 industries × 3 roles × 5 questions of scripts; you pick the 5 most relevant to actually run.\n\n**Note**: AI-generated scripts are the *start*, not the *end*. Real insights come from follow-up questions — and follow-ups must be asked by a human.\n\n### Exercise 3: Competitive Map\n\nRun with Claude:\n1. List every product solving the problem (direct + indirect + DIY)\n2. For each: core promise / pricing / biggest weakness\n3. Mark the \"impossible before AI, possible after\" gaps\n\nThose gaps are your opening.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n| Failure | Why | Fix |\n|---------|-----|-----|\n| **Only talking to willing listeners** | Strong survivor bias | Force 2 \"obvious non-buyers\" per week |\n| **Confusing \"nice\" with \"will pay\"** | These are different things | Ask \"would you buy at $120/yr?\" directly |\n| **Falling for the tech early** | Classic engineer trap | No IDE for the first 30 days |\n| **Competitive map as SWOT** | SWOT doesn't drive decisions | Use \"gap × price tier\" 2D matrix instead |\n| **Expecting AI to judge direction** | AI has no taste | AI generates, you curate |\n\n## Exit Checklist\n\n- [ ] I can explain the problem in 30 seconds\n- [ ] I have 10+ named target customers\n- [ ] I know their current workaround and its cost\n- [ ] I can name the \"impossible-before-AI\" differentiator\n- [ ] 3+ customers verbally committed to try/pay\n\nIf any answer is \"kind of,\" **do not move to MVP**. Go talk to 10 more people.\n\n## Sources\n\n- Based on Anthropic *The Founder's Playbook*, Idea chapter\n- Original PDF: [official download](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n","03-mvp":"# 03. MVP Stage — Build the \"Just Enough\" Version\n\n> **Exit criteria**: First customers can complete the core flow end-to-end without you bailing them out.\n\nThe biggest change in the MVP stage: **writing code is no longer the bottleneck**. One founder + Claude Code ships in a week what a three-person team used to take three months on. But the productivity explosion creates a new trap — **architecture and security debt grow faster than the code itself**.\n\n## Stage Goals\n\n1. **Ship an end-to-end working version**, not a polished partial demo\n2. **Choose an architecture that survives \"still here in 3 months\"**, not \"just get it running\"\n3. **Get security right from day one** — AI-generated code is insecure by default\n4. **Build the customer-feedback channel** ready for Launch\n\n## Architecture & Scope\n\n### Three scope red lines\n\nFast code generation doesn't mean you should build everything. In MVP, hold:\n\n1. **No payments/billing**: use Stripe Payment Links or manual invoices, saves 1 month\n2. **No admin UI**: use Retool / Airtable + direct DB, saves 2 weeks\n3. **No role/permission system**: everyone is admin, add after Launch\n\n> These three save you 2 months. Spend it on customer iteration.\n\n### The \"3-month rule\" for tech choices\n\nAsk every tech decision:\n\n> \"In 3 months I want to change this. What does it cost?\"\n\n- Postgres over NoSQL: complex queries won't block you in 3 months\n- Monolith over microservices: easy to split later; hard to merge\n- One frontend framework, not a mix: easier to hire\n\n**AI won't make these calls for you** — it doesn't know your 3-month vision. That's founder work.\n\n## Security Practices\n\nAI-generated code defaults to these problems:\n\n| Problem | Symptom | Fix |\n|---------|---------|-----|\n| **SQL injection** | String-concat SQL | Force parameterized queries / ORM |\n| **Hardcoded secrets** | API keys in code | `.env` + check .gitignore |\n| **Arbitrary file read** | Path traversal | Whitelist + path.resolve check |\n| **CORS misconfig** | `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` | Explicit domain list |\n| **No rate limit** | One user can DoS the service | Cloudflare / framework middleware |\n\n**Install these guardrails during MVP** — 10x cheaper than fixing after launch.\n\n## Preventing Tech-Debt Explosion\n\n### Set rules for Claude Code\n\nPut `CLAUDE.md` (or `AGENTS.md`) at project root:\n\n```\n- All DB queries use prepared statements\n- No hardcoded secrets\n- Every new feature needs >= 1 integration test\n- PRs over 50 lines require a design note first\n```\n\nThis is the \"project constitution\" the AI reads. Claude Code, Cursor, Aider all honor it.\n\n### Weekly debt sweep\n\nBlock 2 hours weekly, run with Claude:\n\n> \"Scan the project. Find: 1) code duplicated 3+ times; 2) critical paths with no test coverage; 3) places that violate CLAUDE.md.\"\n\nFix the top 3 that week. The rest can wait.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n| Failure | Why | Fix |\n|---------|-----|-----|\n| **\"Demo MVP\"** | Happy path only, breaks under real use | Force 3 customers to run it solo |\n| **Premature performance work** | \"What about 100K users?\" | 100K users is a Scale problem |\n| **Commit-without-reading** | Trust AI output blindly | Read every PR diff |\n| **Build-everything mindset** | \"Don't depend on third parties\" | In MVP, no such thing as over-dependence |\n| **No feedback channel** | Remembering after launch | Set up customer group / feedback button day one |\n\n## Exit Checklist\n\n- [ ] 3 customers can run the core flow without you\n- [ ] All key security items pass (SQL/secrets/CORS/rate limit)\n- [ ] `CLAUDE.md` exists and is actually followed\n- [ ] You can ship a new feature in a week (no tech-debt drag)\n- [ ] Customer feedback channel responds within 24h\n\nIf \"customers can run it solo\" fails, **don't go to Launch**. Keep polishing.\n\n## Sources\n\n- Based on Anthropic *The Founder's Playbook*, MVP chapter\n- Coffee CLI users: run Claude Code as a tab in the Coffee CLI desktop app, and put `CLAUDE.md` at your project root\n- Original PDF: [official download](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n","04-launch":"# 04. Launch Stage — Distinguish PMF from Early Hype\n\n> **Exit criteria**: Core metrics (retention / referral / conversion) stable 4+ weeks without dropping, and you can explain *why*.\n\nLaunch is where founders most easily fool themselves. Twitter praise, Product Hunt #1, press mentions — none of these are PMF. They're **fireworks**. Distinguishing fireworks from real fire is the core skill of this stage.\n\n## Stage Goals\n\n1. **Find a meaningful retention signal** (not vanity metrics)\n2. **Build agentic marketing/ops workflows** to free the founder from repetition\n3. **Decide if it's real PMF or early hype** — Scale or back to MVP\n4. **Shift from \"I push the product\" to \"the product grows itself\"**\n\n## PMF Measurement\n\n### The one question\n\nSean Ellis's classic question still holds:\n\n> \"How would you feel if you could no longer use this product tomorrow?\"\n\nFour answer choices:\n\n- Very disappointed\n- Somewhat disappointed\n- Not disappointed\n- I don't use it anymore\n\n**40%+ choosing \"Very disappointed\"** = you've touched PMF. Below that, keep polishing.\n\n### Three metrics that don't lie\n\nFireworks: DAU, signups, retweet count.\n**Real fire**:\n\n1. **D7 / D30 retention**: still using after 7 days? 30 days?\n2. **Free → paid conversion**: stable ≥ 5% for 4 weeks\n3. **Organic referral rate**: % of new users from \"friend/colleague told me\"\n\n**4 weeks stable** > \"one peak moment\" by 10x.\n\n### Stop counting vanity metrics\n\n| Fireworks | Real fire |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| Product Hunt rank | DAU 30 days after launch |\n| Twitter follower count | Email → signup conversion |\n| Press coverage | Organic search growth |\n| Day-1 signups | D30 retention |\n\n## Agentic Operations\n\nAfter launch, founder attention gets eaten by:\n\n- Customer email / Discord replies\n- Marketing content (tweets, blogs, case studies)\n- Data analysis\n- Customer feedback triage\n\n**Hand all of these to agents**, freeing 80% of your time for what only the founder can do (product direction, key hires, key customers).\n\n### A typical agentic marketing stack\n\n| Work | Tools | Who |\n|------|-------|-----|\n| Feedback triage | Claude + Linear/Notion API | Agent fully auto |\n| Weekly data digest | Claude Code + dbt | Agent auto, founder reviews |\n| Content drafts (tweets, blogs) | Cowork | Agent writes, founder edits |\n| Customer email replies | Claude.ai templates + manual send | Agent drafts, founder sends |\n| Key customer follow-ups | **Founder personally** | Don't let agents touch this |\n\nLast line is non-negotiable: **key customers must be the founder**. Agents cannot replace this.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n| Failure | Why | Fix |\n|---------|-----|-----|\n| **Mistaking fireworks for fire** | Launch-week metrics explode | Wait 4 full weeks before judging |\n| **Premature paid ads** | \"Double the budget, double the traffic\" | Get to 5%/wk organic first |\n| **Founder still manually replying everything** | \"Customer experience\" | Cap at 2h/day manual, rest goes to agents |\n| **Hiring before PMF** | \"3 more engineers and we'll win\" | Hiring without PMF = scaling errors |\n| **Treating PMF as a point** | \"We found PMF!\" | PMF is a state, can be lost, must be defended |\n\n## Exit Checklist\n\n- [ ] D30 retention ≥ 30% (B2B SaaS) or ≥ 40% (high-frequency consumer)\n- [ ] Paid conversion ≥ 5% for 4 consecutive weeks\n- [ ] ≥ 20% of new users from organic referrals\n- [ ] Founder spends ≤ 2h/day on repetitive work\n- [ ] You can explain in one sentence \"why users stay\"\n\nIf \"why users stay\" has no answer, that's not real PMF — that's luck. Keep observing.\n\n## Sources\n\n- Based on Anthropic *The Founder's Playbook*, Launch chapter\n- Sean Ellis PMF Survey template: search \"Sean Ellis PMF Survey\"\n- Original PDF: [official download](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n","05-scale":"# 05. Scale Stage — From Solo to Agentic Team\n\n> **Exit criteria**: Key business flows run when the founder is absent, and the team (humans + agents) ships weekly.\n\nScale is no longer \"founder + AI\" — it's \"founder + team + AI.\" Here you hit the counterintuitive truth of AI-native companies: **your first hire might not be an engineer**. Because AI maxed out engineering capacity, the bottleneck shifts elsewhere — sales, customer success, operations.\n\n## Stage Goals\n\n1. **Switch from \"founder heroics\" to repeatable processes**\n2. **Decide what to hire humans for vs. agents for**\n3. **Build a sustainable financial model** (no longer funding-dependent)\n4. **Protect PMF** — Scale is when PMF is most easily lost\n\n## Hire People vs. Hire Agents\n\nFor each new work category, ask three questions:\n\n1. **Is it judgment-intensive or execution-intensive?**\n   - Execution → agent\n   - Judgment → human\n2. **Does it require customer trust?**\n   - Yes → human (key sales, customer success)\n   - No → agent\n3. **What's the cost of being wrong?**\n   - High (contracts, product direction) → human\n   - Low (drafts, data wrangling) → agent\n\n### Typical split\n\n| Work type | Who | Why |\n|-----------|-----|-----|\n| Sales email drafts | Agent | Execution-heavy, low cost of error |\n| Annual contract negotiation | Human (founder / sales lead) | High cost + trust |\n| Technical documentation | Agent + engineer review | Agent drafts, human verifies |\n| Customer onboarding | Human (B2B) / Agent (B2C) | B2B needs trust, B2C doesn't |\n| Data dashboards | Agent + engineer reviews architecture | Execution-heavy |\n| Hiring interviews | Human | Judgment + inverted trust |\n\n## Financial Model\n\nScale requires switching to \"revenue-driven,\" no more funding life support:\n\n### Three numbers to watch weekly\n\n1. **MRR**: month-over-month growth, target ≥ 15%\n2. **CAC payback**: ≤ 12 months\n3. **Cash runway**: ≥ 12 months\n\n### AI-native financial advantage\n\n| Item | Traditional SaaS | AI-Native |\n|------|-----------------|-----------|\n| Engineer headcount | High | Low (AI replaces) |\n| CS headcount | High | Medium (partial agent) |\n| Marketing content output | Slow + costly | Fast + cheap |\n| Gross margin | 70-80% | 80-90% |\n\n**+10% gross margin is huge** — same revenue, more reinvestment into product and sales.\n\n## Protect PMF\n\nBiggest hidden risk in Scale: **you think you're scaling existing PMF, but it's quietly slipping away**.\n\n### Three early signals\n\n1. **New-cohort retention dropping** (D30 from 40% to 30%)\n2. **Support ticket category shifting** (from \"how to use\" to \"why designed this way\")\n3. **Founder no longer personally meeting customers** (most dangerous)\n\n### How to defend\n\n- **Founder meets ≥ 5 customers/week**, regardless of company size\n- **Weekly feedback walkthrough**: agent triages, founder personally reads top 10\n- **No scaling for scaling's sake** — if growth lags team growth, contract\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n| Failure | Why | Fix |\n|---------|-----|-----|\n| **Premature senior engineer hires** | \"We need to scale engineering\" | AI replaced 80%, hire sales/CS first |\n| **Founder steps back to 'strategy'** | \"Need to think big picture\" | Not yet — keep meeting customers |\n| **Funding-driven** | \"One more round\" | Scale requires revenue-driven |\n| **Copying Silicon Valley playbook** | \"OpenAI/Anthropic do it this way\" | You're not them. You're you. |\n| **Agents running unsupervised** | Full automation, no human gate | Critical decisions need humans |\n\n## Exit Checklist\n\n- [ ] MRR MoM ≥ 15% (6+ consecutive months)\n- [ ] CAC payback ≤ 12 months\n- [ ] Cash runway ≥ 12 months\n- [ ] Key flows documented, new hires onboard in 1 week\n- [ ] Founder still meets ≥ 5 customers/week\n- [ ] D30 retention hasn't dropped\n\nIf 2+ items fail, **go back to Launch** and polish. Scale is an outcome, not a target.\n\n## Sources\n\n- Based on Anthropic *The Founder's Playbook*, Scale chapter\n- Original PDF: [official download](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n","06-stories":"# 06. Founder Stories — Six Companies in the Wild\n\nAnthropic profiled 6 early-stage companies running the AI-native playbook in *The Founder's Playbook*. They span healthcare, enterprise tools, consumer apps, agent infrastructure. Common traits: **small teams, heavy AI use, revenue-driven**.\n\n> Summaries below are organized from Anthropic's official public content. For each company's full story, see the original PDF.\n\n## Ambral\n\n**Industry**: Enterprise apps / automation\n**Model**: Small team + heavy Claude Code use, automating enterprise workflows on a \"pay-for-outcome\" basis\n\n**Key takeaways**:\n- Used AI for code from day one, headcount kept minimal\n- Sales: \"free ROI pilot, then sign\" model\n- Customer success heavily agent-augmented\n\n## Anything\n\n**Industry**: Consumer apps / creative tools\n**Model**: Packages AI capability into tools regular people can use\n\n**Key takeaways**:\n- UX-first: hit the AI \"magic moment\" within 10 seconds\n- Growth via organic user sharing, almost no paid acquisition\n- Founder still personally does product and customer work\n\n## Carta Healthcare\n\n**Industry**: Healthcare / clinical data\n**Model**: AI processing of unstructured clinical trial data\n\n**Key takeaways**:\n- Heavily regulated industry + AI = natural moat\n- Long sales cycle, but high ACV\n- Small engineering team, high ratio of compliance/domain experts\n\n## HumanLayer\n\n**Industry**: Agent infrastructure\n**Model**: A \"human approval\" layer for agents — automation pauses for humans at key decision points\n\n**Key takeaways**:\n- Sells to \"agent builders\" — dev tools play\n- Perfect fit for the Scale \"agent + human\" framework\n- Founders are themselves deep agent-framework users\n\n## Vulcan Technologies\n\n**Industry**: B2B / industrial automation\n**Model**: AI redoing the \"semi-manual\" workflows of legacy industrial software\n\n**Key takeaways**:\n- Old industry + AI = currently most underrated category\n- High customer willingness to pay, long education cycle\n- Sales must be the founder (trust required)\n\n## Sixth company\n\nAnthropic's original publication also profiles one additional company not covered in this course summary. Please refer to the [official PDF](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf) for the complete case.\n\n## Common Patterns\n\nSide-by-side comparison surfaces several shared traits:\n\n| Common pattern | Why it matters |\n|----------------|----------------|\n| **Team < 20 people** | AI lets small teams do what used to take 50 |\n| **Founder/engineer ratio ≥ 1:3** | Leverage from AI, not engineer pile-ups |\n| **CS/sales ratio ≥ 1:1** | Sales still matters, not all product-led |\n| **Gross margin > 80%** | Cost structure advantage from AI |\n| **Founder personally meets customers** | Regardless of size, this never changes |\n\n## How to Read These Stories\n\nThe easy mistake: **remember the story, forget the principle**.\n\nRight way:\n1. Read the case, note \"what did they do right?\"\n2. Map it back to modules 02–05 by stage\n3. Ask yourself: \"At my stage, which move should I copy?\"\n4. **Don't copy the business model wholesale** — you're not them\n\n## Sources\n\n- Full case details: see Anthropic's original PDF at [official download](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/6889473510b50328dbb70ae6/69fe2a55b93bb0732b1fe33c_The-Founders-Playbook-05062026_v3%20%281%29.pdf)\n- Anthropic intro: https://claude.com/blog/the-founders-playbook\n- Individual company websites: search separately\n"}};
